      "id":"culture/australia-culture-blog/2013/oct/02/eddie-perfect-beast-play",
      "sectionId":"culture",
      "sectionName":"Culture",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-02T02:40:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Eddie Perfect: 'a lot of my life is in this play – it was quite cathartic'",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/australia-culture-blog/2013/oct/02/eddie-perfect-beast-play",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/australia-culture-blog/2013/oct/02/eddie-perfect-beast-play",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>The Offspring star celebrated for Shane Warne the Musical and his sharp comedy is taking aim at middle-class treechangers in his new play. And that includes himself</p>",
        "headline":"Eddie Perfect: 'a lot of my life is in this play – it was quite cathartic'",
        "body":"<p>Around the dinner table are three couples in their 30s and 40s. They are treechangers, quite possibly – we're in Healesville, after all, the Yarra Valley beauty spot that has leached artists, food lovers, wine makers, artisans, organic gardeners and young families from Melbourne's suburbs.</p><p>Tonight's dinner will come from a whole cow, purchased by one family and shared with others who might appreciate the journey it has taken from pasture to plate. The cow was to be slaughtered and butchered in front of the group but the mobile butcher has stuck his knife into the carcass, only to messily slice his hand open. Finally he returns from the emergency department. &quot;My God,&quot; one guest quakes. &quot;What would we have done if he hadn't come back?&quot;</p><p>This is the premise of The Beast, <a href=\"http://www.mtc.com.au/plays-and-tickets/2013-mainstage/the-beast/\">Eddie Perfect's new play for the Melbourne Theatre Company</a>. Having been a guest at that very dinner party (&quot;a great dinner party, I hasten to add&quot;) the idea of the beautiful life and death planned for the animal being botched at the final moment – appealed greatly to his impish gene. &quot;What chain reaction would that set off in the lives of these middle-class people, when the best of intentions go astray?&quot; he wonders.</p><p>Perfect is skilled at taking an element of Australia's social status quo and overhauling it just brutally enough to make audiences squirm. From his stand-up career, to the much-lauded Shane Warne the Musical and the recent album and tour <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u8crVin5mC4 \">with musical comedy act Tripod</a>, he wears his love of satire on his sleeve.</p><p>And the stand-up, musician and actor seems decidedly unworried by dumping on his own doorstep. Not only might his friends in Healesville take umbrage – not least because none of the fictional guests have any redeemable features – but the Beast pillories a fair slice of MTC attendees (and Guardian readers), who are his very audience. &quot;But that's me, too,&quot; he protests. &quot;I treechanged and a lot of my life is in this play – it was quite cathartic, really.&quot;</p><figure data-media-id=\"gu-image-418800361\"><img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/1/1380615137478/Eddie-Perfect-008.jpg\" alt=\"Eddie Perfect\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /><figcaption>Eddie Perfect as Mick Holland with Kat Stewart as Billie in Ten's Offspring. Photograph: Network Ten</figcaption></figure><p>Growing up in the blandly white Melbourne beach suburb of Mentone, the son of two high school teachers, resulted in Perfect's morbid fascination with being middle class. &quot;With my generation it's not just about money any more,&quot; he philosophises. &quot;Currency can be about creating things or being an entrepreneur. The coding of what it takes to belong and climb to the next rung is very complicated.&quot;</p><p>He says he's intrigued with what brings friends together. &quot;Sometimes it's because there's history and there's nothing you can do about it; sometimes it's because it's advantageous to your career; or because they've got drugs; or because they can get you a job; or because they're your wife's friends; or they've got kids – that's a new one for me.&quot;</p><p>Perfect and his wife, Lucy, have two young daughters, Kitty and Lottie Lux – although his role as struggling musician Mick Holland in Ten's Offspring has also brought with it a number of fans who might wish he was less happily settled. Is the Green Room, Helpmann and Melbourne International Comedy Festival award-winner concerned that Mick might become <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vfDI2ZjXwK8 \">his Khe Sanh</a>?</p><p>&quot;Khe Sanh would be better – you'd get royalties out of it,&quot; he notes. &quot;It's been really, really good doing Offspring, for a raft of reasons, but I've never really heard anyone say, 'Hey, Mick.' Playing Warnie seems to have been more of a signifier.&quot;</p><p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-OoOtbBQw5E \">Shane Warne the Musical</a>, the production he wrote, composed and starred in, debuted in 2008, toured the country and returned, updated, with a full orchestra in 2013. Perfect picked the cricketer as a subject because he polarises opinion and agitates the tabloids.</p><p>&quot;I really wanted to take care of Shane,&quot; he says. &quot;I was never interested in tearing somebody down. That would be a very negative reality to live in – I was writing the show for three years.&quot;</p><p>Perfect's aim was to allow people to get behind the headlines and see the human side to a tabloid caricature. &quot;Then people can't help but identify with him. He represents everything that's exciting and inspiring about Australia, as well as everything that's embarrassing and cringeworthy.</p><p>&quot;Australians have a real hero system where success isn't the important part – it's more about giving it a go. Everything from Ned Kelly to Gallipoli is about epic failure done with a lot of spunk. The person dies but the subversive spirit lives on.&quot;</p><p>Having borne the brunt of his own media backlash with a song about <a href=\"http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/show-mocks-irwins-death/story-e6freoof-1111112470625 \">Steve Irwin in Babes in the Wood</a> at the Malthouse in 2006 (he points out that 'Die What You Love Doing' was a dig at press headlines, not at Irwin), he's all too aware that people can interpret his work differently.</p><p>The Beast, which stars Tom Budge, Travis Cotton and Virginia Gay, doesn't target people wanting to do good, but those who use causes to boost their social status. He cites armchair activists clicking &quot;Like&quot; on Facebook campaigns and hitting a button on online petitions. &quot;It's tokenism that makes people feel that they are active in the world. But are they? Being able to think in these ways at all is a luxury that we have because of our wealth. We're all complicit in having this huge amount of wealth when most of the world lives in abject poverty.&quot;</p><p>Outside of work, Perfect swears he's not the sort to play devil's advocate. &quot;I'm interested in all different perspectives. Like most people I have a gut reaction to stuff and it takes me a while to work out why. I'm not a big arguer. When I'm emotional I tend to close down because if I spoke it would not be articulate, because I haven't processed why I'm having a reaction.&quot;</p><p>What it all comes down to, he concludes, is this: &quot;Can the ethical things we choose to do ever come close to wiping away the sin of inequality that we live with every day?&quot; And since it's a quandary that continues to make Perfect feel uncomfortable, it's a good bet that The Beast will get under its audience's skin, too.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.mtc.com.au/plays-and-tickets/2013-mainstage/the-beast/\">• The Beast plays at MTC from October 3 to November 9.</a></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418798800|2013-10-07T10:21:29Z|9e202874161ed17673efc024c8f0a0656d8db1a9 -->",
