      "id":"culture/2013/oct/01/crafty-art-women-review",
      "sectionId":"culture",
      "sectionName":"Culture",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-01T03:30:27Z",
      "webTitle":"Funny, crafty women make a serious point about our expectations of art",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/oct/01/crafty-art-women-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/2013/oct/01/crafty-art-women-review",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>Adrienne Doig's work is pretty damn funny</p>",
        "headline":"Funny, crafty women make a serious point about our expectations of art",
        "body":"<p>Adrienne Doig&rsquo;s work is pretty damn funny. Her <a href=\"http://www.martinbrownecontemporary.com/doig13.html\">exhibition</a> Splendid at Martin Browne Contemporary in Sydney is a show of self-portraits: at times the artist appears with her back turned, or just her smart red shoes visible; at others she holds up signs in the manner of Wile E Coyote from those old Warner Bros. cartoons: SPLENDID, GOOD ENOUGH and VERY INTERESTING. In one, the most telling perhaps, Doig carries a placard that reads FEMINIST CLICHE.</p> <p>Doig&rsquo;s chosen medium is fabric, and her techniques include applique, patchwork and embroidery. Having sourced unfinished patchwork projects from eBay that dated to the 1930s and 40s, she uses them as her base, overlaying images of herself, often in full figure, posing against the intense patterns, her eyes affixed defiantly at the viewer, or away at something more interesting. The feminist cliche bit is presumably Doig&rsquo;s acknowledgement that a focus on handicrafts and other &ldquo;women&rsquo;s work&rdquo; folk arts has long been a way for female artists to make a statement about the cultural prejudices held against &ldquo;arts and crafts&rdquo;.</p> <p>There&rsquo;s a good humour in Doig&rsquo;s work that defuses polemic into something more approachable and kind-hearted. Yet that feminist philosophy remains. Even if they have a degree of irony, these are still works that many would consider to be more craft than art and given the long history of artists who have defied that categorisation, it&rsquo;s interesting that it is the decorative quality of the work which is seen to define it as &ldquo;not serious&rdquo;.</p> <p>When Del Kathryn Barton <a href=\"http://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/2013/\">won the 2013 Archibald prize</a> this year for hugo, a portrait of Hugo Weaving, a common refrain echoing across social media was that the work was &ldquo;decorative&rdquo; and thus not worthy of serious consideration. Whether the work is &ldquo;good&rdquo; or &ldquo;bad&rdquo; is a whole other issue &ndash; but the response was a reminder of the antiquated values that are placed on the techniques and styles of contemporary art making. Serious art can be many things, but not decorative.</p> <p>&ldquo;Decorative&rdquo; is a poorly defined term, but it is usually equated with work that displays conspicuous craft skill, has probably taken many hours to complete, and it has distinctive and obvious attractive qualities. Both Barton and Doig&rsquo;s work have exactly those qualities. In addition, when Barton first won the Archibald prize in 2008, it was also with a <a href=\"http://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/2008/\">self-portrait</a>, which included her two children. And when it comes to serious art, mothers and their kids won&rsquo;t do.</p> <p>Doig&rsquo;s show coincides with <a href=\"http://www.brendamaygallery.com.au/details.php?exhibitionID=196\">Sugar Sugar</a>, a group show at Brenda May Gallery also in Sydney. Curated by Megan Fizell, this is a 10-woman show where all the works are created using sugar, many taking the shape of other &ldquo;non-serious&rdquo; art forms &ndash; cakes, jewellery, flower-arranging and cameos. The works themselves are mostly conceptual pieces that play on the idea of transience, value and permanence, given their limited shelf life.</p> <p>Among the pieces are Matina Bourmas&rsquo;s performance <a href=\"http://www.brendamaygallery.com.au/enlarge_ex.php?workID=36547&amp;exhibitionID=196\">Gifting</a> where the artist, using cake icing, applies delicate doily-like patterns to the gallery walls (daily 2.30-3pm) and Stephanie Jones&rsquo;s series The Traceries, that uses royal icing in petri dishes to create minutely patterned cameos. Janet Tavener has made <a href=\"http://www.feastingonart.com/2013/09/janet-tavener-asparagus-pie.html\">fake cakes</a> using sugar paste and food colouring and Claire McArdle presents jewellery made from gold and chocolate. Judith Klausner&rsquo;s <a href=\"http://www.brendamaygallery.com.au/enlarge_ex.php?workID=36277&amp;exhibitionID=196\">Oreo Cameo</a>&nbsp;series presents classic cameos carved from the chocolate cookies, the classicism of their style ironically undercut by their ephemeral nature.</p> <p>The work in both Sugar Sugar and in Doig&rsquo;s exhibition knowingly play with values and expectations, putting these traditionally female craft skills into the context of a contemporary art exhibition. It may not do much to alter the deeply ingrained prejudices of apparently open-minded viewers of art but it&rsquo;s nice to be reminded of how arbitrary our value system is.</p> <p>The heretical notion that even those highest of high art forms such as photography, minimalist painting and sculpture could be just as easily considered decor as brainy and high falutin&rsquo; intellectualism, pretty much neutralises the non-serious tag for decorative work. A <a href=\"http://www.55sydenhamrd.com/marilyn-schneider\">show</a> by Marilyn Schneider looked for all the world like a very serious investigation of abstract sculpture &ndash; and while it was that, it was also a canny piece of appropriation. Schneider&rsquo;s work had taken the look and feel of corporate signage used at trade fairs and, out of context, she had created an elegant but ambiguous object that was neither art nor craft. If corporate signage isn&rsquo;t the ultimate example of the decorative, then what is?</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418602729|2013-10-07T10:21:29Z|3944280cb38d13f4d87d98061c8b26e72de882d3 -->",
